description: Almost all colleges have regulations for the establishment of student committees. The purpose of these elections is to provide students with a democratic form of responsibility. Students who participated in the election shared their views and opinions and asked other students to vote for them. A lot happened- memes, posters, messages on groups, spam, DMs, Manifestos, Posters, claims of Branchism xD and whatnot. One of the best-organized chaos you would ever witness.

The first semester had gone by at breakneck speed. Our end-semester exams were done and we had a short break(did we tho:| ). So, by utilizing it to do something for everyone’s interest in coding, our Tech-Secretary Tabish organized Code-topia Workshops on 21st March and 26th march. The motive of these workshops was to help particularly those, who were new to coding and its essentials. Overall, the event was great with some extraordinary cooperation in the (informal,xD) Tech Council.

A case study is one of the best teaching tools to improve and test students' practical knowledge. On these principles, the IIC organized the case study competition, Avadhan, in virtual mode from February 19 to 21. It took place in two stages, preliminaries and finals, with a large number of freshers participating, helping the event to develop successfully. As a result, two students from our batch, Divya Harshita, and Srishti entered the finals with a highly impressive case study report.

A session was held by CDC to have an interaction with all the fresher girls, in order to convey some important information and also address queries and concerns related to internships, placements, and general career development. Ms. Shrishti Shrivastava took the honor to do so and became a close acquaintance with all girls of our batch, and encouraged them to follow their ambitions.

The Junior Tech Secretary and his council of techies organized this amazing competition among the freshers, between 13 -14 April. This challenge was completely based on how quickly one can code the right code for the given problem statements. The champ among us was Devesh, with the runner-up being Sahaja. Harrithha secured third place.

During the course of CS101, students got to complete their project with their classmates, which ideally created talks and unused thoughts! After the end of our semester, any group was free to utilize 15 minutes on a gmeet with Rajshekhar sir and our batchmates, in any way they wish, in order to exhibit their work. Sir provided the groups with valuable inputs and feedback for their projects and the exhibition was thoroughly enjoyed by all.

IIT Dharwad’s E-Summit, being facilitated by the IIC, was one of the major events that was held during our semester break. The Entrepreneurial fest highlighted well-known identities, who gave in-depth knowledge regarding numerous things and motivated us to cultivate and support our imaginative thoughts, developments, and our other interesting abilities. We prepared ourselves for three days of fun. Apart from gaining knowledge from the event, we took part in competitions and quiz, with astounding prizes being up for grabs.

This was Eunoia’s annual debate challenge with prelims, semi-finals, and finals rounds. Given the circumstances, it was conducted totally online. It was a brilliant opportunity to pitch in and express views and thoughts on different topics, including personal attacks,xD. It was exceptional as in spite of being freshers, the champs were from our batch, Altmash and Tanish.

Fanta-Six was the event conducted by Aditya Kalyani, Rajashekar, Tanish, Varad, Hari, and Rahul Prajapat. The Fanta-Six was the FYSC’s version of the IPL Fantasy league and was organized keeping in mind the large cricket fan-base that you see everywhere, including our batch. There was a players’ auction before the beginning of IPL, and this event was amazing, with teams offering huge prices for batsmen, eventually left with less to nothing. Fanta-Six ran parallel with the complete IPL season(first half) and saw Team Dhurander dominating everywhere. After starting at the bottom, Team Simps managed to dominate the second position, leaving other teams to battle it out closely. Totally 8 groups of 4-5 students took part and a rule book for Fanta-Six was meticulously prepared by the organising team. Unfortunately, Fanta-Six had to be suspended in between, just like the IPL. People remain eager to witness its restart and hopefully we get to see the winners at the end of IPL

College life provides you much more than just a degree, so buckle up your seats and get ready to experience as much fun as possible. The fresher’s intro video was organized to fill the freshers with inspiration, as numerous people may feel confused and have fear within their hearts as they begin this modern stage of life. The video stays funny throughout, with Altmash stealing the show.. 'Phukesh Phukesh, full Phukesh…..'

“Our whole lives have driven up to this,” we clowned to ourselves in mid-March. When shelter-in-place orders came down, millions of individuals switched to online meets and so did we, with google meets and discord servers. It was pretty common for us at that time to play games and discuss stuff online. Our Cult-Sec, Smriti and her buddies organized a games night for  us freshers. Different games such as ludo, scribbl,uno, trivia test, among us, and meme mania were conducted. Incredible cooperation from the 2020 batch with full bliss and parcels of fun was amazing to witness, including one of our extraordinary professors, Dr. Sagnik Sen, who took interest for participating in the same (guided by samy to play among us, xD). We got our winners as Aaryya das for the trivia quiz and Sadock Chakma for meme mania.

“We have been incapable to move our university which we had now no longer seen. Our home is presently a college school, living beneath our roof advantage from quick /moderate web, old/modern tablets, and a full cooler of pdf/mails. The network could be a huge challenge. many still have no access to modern gadgets, appropriate infrastructure, regular electricity,  etc., it seems to institute only jobs to finish out us in each and every semester. A stressed-out brain does not learn. “These were the brief reactions of our batchmates regarding not opening the campus. A bold initiative by Tarun was to raise voices of the students against them, by mailing(spamming, xD) the Dean and the Directors and whosoever’s email-id we obtained. Some seniors were in favor of us, some were not, giving us some funny reactions. As expected, no reply came from the institute regarding the opening of campus for the 2020 batch.

After witnessing the huge success of our first games night,  our Cult-Sec, with her buddies, once again came up to crush boredom in many ways and conducted the same show up once again in a new improved manner. Many new interesting games were included along with the classics. Chess, CODM, Free fire, Valorant, Pokémon showdown, stumble guys, Skribbl, Codenames, Among Us, Ludo, Psych, Garctic Phone were the games conducted with efficient management involved.  As expected, the entire batch took part enthusiastically and collaborated with each other, with a friendly blissful environment being maintained throughout the event. The top three positions were secured by Devesh, Varad and Rajat respectively, with Akash and Keshav securing a consolidatory fourth.

“Chess is life scaled-down. Chess can be a fight, a battle of minds and tactics.” A chess competition was organized by our Board Games Secretary Aditya Kalyani. A team leader was selected for each team based on the team leader tournament that was conducted before. The team leader further selected the team members based on the intra-branch tournaments conducted. Many first-year undergraduates took part enthusiastically which included Aditya Kalyani, Priyanshu Jayara, Borella Bharat Chandra, Aryan D Trimukhe, Lokesh B Jogi, Deepu Kumar, Aryaman J Singh.  After a lot of fun, victory, defeat, stalemates, and checkmates, the team of the Electrical department emerged as winners.

Among the many events organized, there was great participation from IIT Dharwad. For the mid-prep event-“ISRO web-based visualization apparatus for astrosat observations”, triumph was on the title for the IITDh team, which included three of our freshers girls- Sayali, Smriti and Manvi, who cleared all the challenging software specifications and evaluation criteria, and won the bronze medal for our Institute. Kudos!! to their dedication and hard work.

Online classes are ,as always, over our heads, and in the middle of this shit, everyone looked at their screens with shock, as we were instructed to give our midsems OFFLINE, in KVs. After collecting all stats from students, with reasons why KVs are not convenient, an email was sent to the Academic Staff. The amazing reply we got was- “Nothing is impossible”, basically shutting our voices down. We all gave our exams offline, with many facing issues. From the Security Guard not allowing us inside, to the Principal arriving two hours late and what not. The only good thing was that at least a few of us met each other. All the endeavors by students to dodge this were undertaken with no success.

A group of enthusiastic gamers from our batch got together and made nice progress in the crazy world of minecraft. Description of events by Hari: 'First we started off stranded near a mineshaft underneath a cave and we made our way to create our first base(temporary) inside the cave and we continued mining and dying to the Endermen.Then we got good weapons and armour and created our nether portal. We then travelled across the nether and made our way to a grassland and found a few horses and made our final base.'

The Open Mic event- “CITY LIGHTS”, by Eunoia, provided an opportunity for performers to gain experience by performing in front of a live audience and entertaining them. The Open Mic event gave the performer the stage to present their hobbies and express themselves in their unique way. The event kicked off with Samy’s presentation of his Graphic Designing pironess, which he is very well known for in our institute. Harrithha and Tabish mesmerized us with their melodious singing. Meghana showed off her dance moves and Hari rocked the stage with his Piano performance, with his piano rendition of AOT being the most memorable performance.

A great introduction program makes a big difference, first-year students feel energized around the beginning of college and Orientation smoothens this move to campus life and the autonomy that comes with it. There were numerous introduction programs that sadly remained completely online at that time. Different sorts of sessions were organised, which include: Director’s address, Student Mentorship Program, YourDost, Workshop on music, Talk to the theatre, Samwaad, Ice breaker, Gender Sensitization workshop, and finally, but not the heaviest, Lunch with seniors.

A few online musical concerts organised by Rhapsody, the music club of our institute. The events were streamed live on YouTube and lots of participation was witnessed. The events were lit, especially the one with Frizzel D’Souza

A Robotics workshop for our batch was conducted by the extraordinary NKC to present  Arduino and design basic circuits virtually on tinkercad with a project of traffic light circuit design. The second session started with the introduction of IR sensors and motor controllers and ended up in making line follower Robot(circuit design, programming the controls, and simulation using Webot). Freshers appeared intrigued and felt highly interested.

“To Catch it and quiz it” was the theme behind this quiz. It was the first event for us and many of us participated in this quiz. The quiz had many interesting questions, related to modern technologies and a few modern tech companies. We also got introduced to what IIC is and what it does.
